Project Title: CRIME RATE ANALYSIS¶

About the Dataset¶

This dataset provides information on violent crime rates in American cities between 1957 and 2015. It consists of 2829 rows and 15 columns. The columns include eport_year, agency_code, agency_jurisdiction, population, violent_crimes, homicides, rapes, assaults, robberies, months_reported, crimes_percapita, homicides_percapita, rapes_percapita, assaults_percapita, and robberies_percapita.

Dataset source: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/marshallproject/crime-rates¶

OBJECTIVES OF THE ANALYSIS¶

The dataset is wide but for the purpose of this project, we will keep the analysis simple and direct it to answer the following objective questions. The objectives of this analysis is to answer the following questions:

What has been the trend of crime rate reported in each agency jurisdiction? DId any agency jurisdiction experience any sudden hike in the rate of crime reported?

There seems to be outliers in the dataset. For the homicides, rapes, assaults, robberies, and population columns, there seems to be a huge difference between the 75th percentile and the maximum. This signifies the presence of outliers. Let's take a better look at the outlier by considering a box plot.

#Since we have about 70 different agency_jurisdictions, the best plot is to separate each of the different jurisdiction
import seaborn as sns


df["report_year"] = df["report_year"].astype(int)

# Calculate the decade
df['decade'] = (df['report_year'] // 10) * 10

# Create a FacetGrid
g = sns.FacetGrid(df, col='agency_jurisdiction', col_wrap=5, height=3)
g.map(sns.lineplot, 'decade', 'violent_crimes')

# Customize the appearance
g.set_axis_labels('Decade', 'Total Violent Crimes')
g.set_titles('{col_name}')
g.add_legend()

plt.show()

C:\Users\User\anaconda3\Anaconda\Lib\site-packages\seaborn\axisgrid.py:118: UserWarning: The figure layout has changed to tight
  self._figure.tight_layout(*args, **kwargs)

Insight¶

  • Chicago, IL , Los Angeles, CA both experienced an increase from 1970 to 1990 after which they experienced decrease in the violent crime rate from 1990 to 2010.

  • New York City, NY experienced a huge decrease in violent crime rate after a little hike from 1970 to 1980

  • All other jurisdiction shows little or no change in violent crime rate from 1970 to 2010 with the exception of Charlotte, NC, Cleveland, OH, Los Angeles, CA and New York City, NY.

  • Charlotte, NC jurisdiction experienced an increase in violent crime rate while Cleveland, OH jurisdiction experienced a decrease.

Conclusion¶

  • Crime started rising around 1960 in the New York City for unknown reasons. Crime started decreasing in 1991, due to a new mayor and his 'get tough’ policing policies.

  • In California, there was a lot of competition for the crack market from the late 1980s to the 1990s in the inner city community, and that led to a large numberof homicide and other vices.
